          "value": "xywh=pixel:861.2111816406248,4613.071289062501,3782.512207031251,610.250244140625"
        }
      },
      "@context": "http://www.w3.org/ns/anno.jsonld",
      "type": "Annotation",
      "body": [
        {
          "type": "TextualBody",
          "purpose": "transcribing",
          "value": "What does it mean to be called to worship? All serious activity requires preparation. The prayers\nand blessings that precede Bar'chu are warm-ups for the individual. Now communal prayer\nbegins. The leader asks, “Are you ready to pray?\" And we respond, \"Yes! Let us pray!\"\nadapted from Richard Levy"
        }
      ],
      "created": "2026-07-11T20:05:46.401Z",
      "creator": {
        "isGuest": true,
        "id": "2vi94ExIjdtwM7ddi4wa"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "fe772466-a6a8-4460-ab83-1a05fbb91d95",
      "target": {
        "source": "mishkan:page:051c3a8f-0c58-444d-ada6-1a4ea721005d",
        "type": "SpecificResource",
        "selector": {
          "type": "FragmentSelector",
          "conformsTo": "http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/",
          "value": "xywh=pixel:872.9335937499999,5205.79833984375,3717.57568359375,1081.885986328125"
        }
      },
      "@context": "http://www.w3.org/ns/anno.jsonld",
      "type": "Annotation",
      "body": [
        {
          "type": "TextualBody",
          "purpose": "transcribing",
          "value": "Baruch atah, Praised are You: So important was the recitation of the Shma to our ancestors in Eretz Yisrael, that they introduced it with a blessing. That blessing fell out of use over a thousand years ago; we reclaim it here as part of our liturgical heritage.\nThere are three main avenues by which one arrives at meaning in life. The first is by creating a life or doing a deed. The second is by experiencing something or encountering someone; in other words, meaning can be found not only in work but also in love. Third: even the helpless victim of a hopeless situation, facing a fate that cannot be changed, may rise above himself, grow beyond himself, and by so doing, change himself. Viktor E. Frankl",
          "language": "en"
        }
      ],
